projectcomments:
Eclipse has two types of agreements. One for committers, and one for contributors.

All commits are signed-off-by in git using a DCO (we call it a CoO - Certificate of Originality)

signedby[other]: The above should be true; we haven't managed to extend to Github contributions yet
projectcomments: Our Committer's Agreement is best seen as a promise of and a reminder of good behaviour. There is no copyright assignment.

projectsize[other]: 271 contributes all time; 31 in the last 12 months
policyelements[other]: License is per source file.   New code is encouraged to be BSD
projectcomments: The history of OpenAFS is that its initial code contribution was IBM publishing the "IBM AFS 3.6" source code to its DeveloperWorks site under the IBM Public License 1.0.   The ownership of that code still belongs to IBM but IBM does not run the project nor has it ever been willing to grant ownership of the code copyright or the trademarks or patents to a legal or non-legal entity.  There is no contributor agreement because it is unclear whom would have a right to issue one.

The CLA says I am supposed to have signed it and mailed it in, but I have not done so and my contributions continue to be merged. It is possible that because they are documentation fixes, they don't care as much.
The requirement to sign the CLA is a major hurdle that discourages many individual contributors, and prevents some companies participating

signedby[other]: Developers working for Wikimedia Foundation agree to licensing in their employment contracts
projectcomments: has caused trouble in the past because of wish to relicense some Apache? code regarding Lucene

policyelements[other]: No explicit policy, but DCO is strongly recommended.
signedby[other]: Not required, but DCO strongly recommended.
noagreement[other]: The project had CAA, but it was abolished.
